Here is the translation:

He stayed up all night around him, therefrom the vales came forth trembling;
My maternal uncle was a devotee in my family, very old near his knee was bent.

He wore a beautiful cloak, a golden garment; 
His sleep was pleasant, he got up at dawn, pitiful one, 
The night had stayed with him, the day had gone away, merciful one.

Here is the translation:

Those who came from there, know blessed devotees living; 
From there, the work of fulfillment went on, came with mercy and helped the village.

Here is the translation:

Did festive joy after doing, took away my beloved's crest; 
Told to keep coming as I am attired thus, will come back with my own country.

Santos jaao hae suhu maali, faro deshodesham maandi;
Je ne bhanu hoi te bhanjyo, suhu niyamamaan kushal rahejay.

(Note: The number "47" at the end is likely a reference to the source or a note about the couplet, which I have not included in my response as per your request.)
